<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-08-26T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-08-26T08:00:00-05:00" n="292" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d292">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7251: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-26T16:00:00+03:00">August 26, 1935—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received August 26—12:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>389. Doctor Yen, Chinese Ambassador, stated to me yesterday that his
                            latest information from Nanking indicated that the Chinese Government
                            felt compelled to accept the Japanese demand for “full economic
                            cooperation”.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>